  "title": "Honey That Never Dies",
  "units": [
    {
      "t": "weave",
      "l1": "Honey",
      "l2": "Honig",
      "lemma": "Honig",
      "pos": "noun",
      "gender": "m",
      "gloss": "honey",
      "ipa": "ˈhoːnɪç",
      "weave_priority": 2
    },
    {
      "t": "text",
      "l1": " is one of the few things in the "
    },
    {
      "t": "weave",
      "l1": "world",
      "l2": "Welt",
      "lemma": "Welt",
      "pos": "noun",
      "gender": "f",
      "gloss": "world",
      "ipa": "vɛlt",
      "weave_priority": 4
    },
    {
      "t": "text",
      "l1": " that never goes bad. Archaeologists once opened an ancient Egyptian tomb and found a clay "
    },
    {
      "t": "weave",
      "l1": "jar",
      "l2": "Glas",
      "lemma": "Glas",
      "pos": "noun",
      "gender": "n",
      "gloss": "jar",
      "ipa": "ɡlaːs",
      "weave_priority": 5
    },
    {
      "t": "text",
      "l1": " of honey inside. It had rested there for more than three thousand "
    },
    {
      "t": "weave",
      "l1": "years",
      "l2": "Jahren",
      "lemma": "Jahr",
      "pos": "noun",
      "gender": "n",
      "case": "dat",
      "gloss": "year",
      "ipa": "jaːɐ̯",
      "weave_priority": 5
    },
    {
      "t": "text",
      "l1": ", and yet it was still good to "
    },
    {
      "t": "weave",
      "l1": "eat",
      "l2": "essen",
      "lemma": "essen",
      "pos": "verb",
      "gloss": "to eat",
      "ipa": "ˈɛsən",
      "weave_priority": 7
    },
    {
      "t": "text",
      "l1": ". The secret lies in the honey itself. It holds very little "
    },
    {
      "t": "weave",
      "l1": "water",
      "l2": "Wasser",
      "lemma": "Wasser",
      "pos": "noun",
      "gender": "n",
      "gloss": "water",
      "ipa": "ˈvasɐ",
      "weave_priority": 3
    },
    {
      "t": "text",
      "l1": ", so bacteria cannot grow in it. Bees also add a mild acid that keeps it safe for a very long time. Because of this, honey almost never spoils if you keep the jar closed and dry. People in many old cultures used it not only as sweet "
    },
    {
      "t": "weave",
      "l1": "food",
      "l2": "Essen",
      "lemma": "Essen",
      "pos": "noun",
      "gender": "n",
      "gloss": "food",
      "ipa": "ˈɛsən",
      "weave_priority": 4
    },
    {
      "t": "text",
      "l1": ", but also as medicine for wounds. A simple jar of honey can outlive whole empires."
    }
  ]
}
